  "name": "Multiple Sclerosis - Comprehensive Provider Query",
  "description": "Simulates a neurologist identifying their complete MS patient population. The PheKB MS algorithm uses 2+ ICD-9 340 codes (Type 1) OR demyelinating disease codes plus MS-specific medications (Type 2). Real-world identification primarily unions: MS diagnosis codes and MS DMT prescriptions. Because MS DMTs are highly specific (unlike GERD's PPIs), the union has minimal overcounting noise — most DMT-treated patients without an MS dx code are simply pending documentation rather than alternative-indication prescribing.",
  "prompt": "I need to identify my complete multiple sclerosis patient population for a treatment optimization quality initiative. From clinical experience, MS patients are documented in different ways: most have a formal diagnosis code by clinical course (RRMS, SPMS, or PPMS), and most are on disease-modifying therapy. A small number on DMTs may not have a formal MS diagnosis coded yet, especially if recently diagnosed or transferred from another practice.\n\nPlease run multiple FHIR queries to capture the full population:\n1. Patients with any multiple sclerosis diagnosis (parent MS, RRMS, SPMS, PPMS, or anatomic variants)\n2. Patients prescribed MS disease-modifying therapy (natalizumab, alemtuzumab, ocrelizumab, dimethyl fumarate, fingolimod)\n\nFor each query, return the matching resources. I want the union of all patients found. Unlike many phenotypes, the union should have minimal overcount because MS DMTs are highly specific to MS.",
  "metadata": {
    "implementation_guide": "US Core 5.0.0",
    "multi_query": true,
    "algorithm_path": "comprehensive",
    "algorithm_path_description": "Union of MS dx codes (Paths A+B) and DMT Rx (Paths A+C). Path C is small (~10%) because DMT specificity is high. The union accurately approximates the true MS-treated population.",
